MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 1549345733}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: aceea7582206cfb4893c3a26d259b2c4, type: 3}
  m_Name: 
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  audioClips:
  - {fileID: 8300000, guid: cb4648b77e219c9418ec18530b537b5b, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 8300000, guid: 547c9b13b50d9ef46ab142e5ea1574b7, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 8300000, guid: b72f2e67051081f40a37aa181428b813, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 8300000, guid: 051a6733b96ede445b8d3baa344d8644, type: 3}
  - {fileID: 8300000, guid: 5ce35275ecc87554e9705f86bf467905, type: 3}
  textForClips:
  - For this exercise you will have to translate words into binary numbers.    Use
    the buttons on the CPU Register to spell out a word, one letter at a time.
  - Imagine you have a box of light switches. Each switch can be either 'ON' or 'OFF'.
    In computers, 'ON' is called "1" and 'OFF' is called "0". This system of using
    just two numbers is called binary. Computers use binary because they have billions
    of tiny switches, called transistors, that can be either on or off.
  - When these switches are lined up in a row, their positions represent different
    numbers. The switch on the right might be 1, the next 2, then 4, then 8, doubling
    each time. By using different combinations of 'ON' and 'OFF', computers can represent
    any number or piece of information, just like we use combinations of digits to
    write numbers.
  - Imagine you have a secret decoder ring that turns letters, numbers, and symbols
    into special codes. ASCII is like that ring for computers! It gives each character
    a unique code, made of 1's and 0's, so computers can understand and use them.
    So, when you type the letter "A" on your keyboard, the computer sees its special
    ASCII code and knows you mean the letter "A".
  - The ascii values you need to put into the register are listed out under the row
    of transistors.
  audioSource: {fileID: 1429072682}
  textDisplay: {fileID: 1873192258}
